    description: 'Colorectal peritoneal metastases (CPM) affect 10–15% of patients with colorectal cancer at diagnosis (synchronous) and develop metachronously in up to 25% of those with stage II–III disease. The peritoneum is the second most common site of CRC metastasis after the liver, and unlike haematogenous spread, CPM are characterised by locoregional tumour biology that creates a therapeutic window for locoregional treatment. CRS+HIPEC remains the only potentially curative strategy for selected patients, with mitomycin C now preferred over oxaliplatin following PRODIGE 7 data, and molecular testing (RAS, BRAF, MMR) is mandatory to guide both systemic therapy sequencing and surgical candidacy. The PSOGI Consensus 2022 conditionally recommends CRS+HIPEC in selected patients while ESMO 2023 continues to advocate for enrolment in clinical trials.',
