    description: 'Gastric cancer is the fifth most common cancer globally and peritoneal dissemination occurs in 10–20% at diagnosis, developing in 40–60% during the disease course, representing the most common metastatic pattern for diffuse-type gastric cancer. Unlike CRC and ovarian cancer, CRS+HIPEC for gastric PM remains strictly investigational and should only be offered within clinical trials. GASTRICHIP (JAMA Surgery 2021, n=183) was a negative RCT — CRS+HIPEC with cisplatin did not improve 5-year OS over CRS alone (18.8% vs 15.8%, HR 0.87, NS). Signet ring cell histology, PCI >6, and progression on systemic chemotherapy are contraindications. FLOT4 (Lancet 2019) established FLOT as the perioperative standard for resectable gastric cancer. PIPAC (cisplatin 7.5 mg/m² + doxorubicin 1.5 mg/m²) has its strongest evidence base in gastric PM and represents the appropriate palliative strategy.',
    epidemiology: 'Gastric cancer: 5th most common cancer globally, ~1 million new cases/year. PM at diagnosis: 15–20% of patients. Signet ring cell histology: 30–40% of gastric cancers, highest risk for PM. Lauren diffuse type: PM risk 50–60% lifetime. HER2 overexpression/amplification: 15–20% (intestinal type predominantly). EBV-associated gastric cancer: 9–10% (distinct molecular subtype, high MSI, good immunotherapy response). PD-L1 CPS ≥5: ~55–60% of gastric cancers.',
