    description: 'Primary peritoneal carcinoma (PPC) is a malignancy histologically identical to high-grade serous ovarian carcinoma (HGSOC) but arising from the secondary Müllerian system (peritoneal mesothelium) with absent or minimal ovarian involvement (<5mm tumour on ovarian surface). It is classified together with HGSOC and fallopian tube carcinoma as "pelvic serous carcinoma" in ESMO 2023 and NCCN 2024 guidelines, and treatment follows HGSOC protocols without distinction. CRS+HIPEC with cisplatin (OVHIPEC-1 regimen: 100 mg/m², 40°C, 90 min) is standard of care at interval debulking surgery after NACT. BRCA1/2 germline testing is mandatory — PPC patients have a higher germline BRCA prevalence than unselected HGSOC due to ascertainment bias in high-risk women who underwent prophylactic bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy (BSO).',
    epidemiology: 'PPC accounts for 5–15% of all "ovarian cancer" diagnoses. Exclusively in women. Notable subgroup: women who underwent prophylactic BSO for BRCA1/2 germline mutation — residual 10–15% lifetime risk of PPC persists even after prophylactic BSO. BRCA1 carriers: residual risk ~4.3% after BSO; BRCA2 carriers: ~3.5%. Age at diagnosis: 60–70 years (similar to HGSOC). Most present as FIGO IIIC or IV by definition (ovaries spared but peritoneum diffusely involved).',
    histology: 'High-grade serous carcinoma (HGSOC) histology in >95% — morphologically indistinguishable from ovarian HGSOC. By definition: normal or minimally involved ovaries (<5mm tumour on ovarian surface). Fallopian tube often uninvolved. Diffuse peritoneal studding with omental cake. Same nuclear atypia, psammoma bodies, and aberrant TP53 mutation pattern (block-positive or null) as HGSOC. Distinction from HGSOC is pathological, not clinical or therapeutic.',
    ihc: ['PAX8+', 'WT-1+', 'CK7+', 'CA125+', 'p53 aberrant (HGSOC pattern — block or null)', 'ER+ (variable)', 'PR+/−', 'CK20-', 'CDX2-', 'FRα (folate receptor alpha) — test for mirvetuximab eligibility'],
